editorial:
**Approach — binary search on starts**: Build a list of `(start, originalIndex)` sorted by `start`. For each interval, binary-search the smallest start `>= end`. That start's original index is the answer; if no such start, `-1`.

```javascript
function findRightSlot(slots) {
  const sorted = slots.map((s, i) => [s[0], i]).sort((a, b) => a[0] - b[0]);
  const starts = sorted.map(p => p[0]);
  const idx = sorted.map(p => p[1]);
  function lowerBound(target) {
    let lo = 0, hi = starts.length;
    while (lo < hi) {
      const mid = (lo + hi) >> 1;
      if (starts[mid] < target) lo = mid + 1;
      else hi = mid;
    }
    return lo;
  }
  const out = new Array(slots.length).fill(-1);
  for (let i = 0; i < slots.length; i++) {
    const pos = lowerBound(slots[i][1]);
    out[i] = pos < starts.length ? idx[pos] : -1;
  }
  return out;
}
```

**Time**: O(n log n). **Space**: O(n).

Unique starts → lowerBound is unambiguous; if duplicates allowed, define which to pick (smallest index?) and adjust.

