editorial:
**Weighted interval scheduling — DP + binary search**:

1. Sort promos by `end`.
2. Let `pred(i)` = the largest index `j < i` with `end[j] <= start[i]` (or `-1`).
3. `dp[i] = max(dp[i-1], value[i] + dp[pred(i)])` — either skip `i`, or take it and add the best result from non-conflicting predecessors.

Binary-search for `pred(i)` keeps each step O(log n). Pure greedy (max non-overlap count) doesn't apply when values vary.

```javascript
function maxPromoValue(promos) {
  if (promos.length === 0) return 0;
  const arr = promos.slice().sort((a, b) => a[1] - b[1]);
  const ends = arr.map(p => p[1]);
  const n = arr.length;
  function pred(i) {
    let lo = 0, hi = i;
    const target = arr[i][0];
    while (lo < hi) {
      const mid = (lo + hi) >> 1;
      if (ends[mid] <= target) lo = mid + 1;
      else hi = mid;
    }
    return lo - 1;
  }
  const dp = new Array(n + 1).fill(0); // dp[i] = best using arr[0..i-1]
  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    const take = arr[i][2] + dp[pred(i) + 1];
    const skip = dp[i];
    dp[i + 1] = Math.max(take, skip);
  }
  return dp[n];
}
```

**Time**: O(n log n) — sort + n binary searches.
**Space**: O(n) — dp + ends.

Touching is allowed because `pred` uses `ends[mid] <= start`, not strict `<`.
